## Token-saving offload to cheapskate

You have a cheapskate MCP server registered. It exposes two tools:

- `run_task(task_type, criteria, payload)`: routes ONE subtask to the cheapest model that clears
  the acceptance criteria (local first, cloud only on escalation), verifies and repairs the output,
  and returns a result with `route` (local|cloud|refused), `ok`, `retries`, `escalated`, and
  `output`.
- `econ_report(month?)`: the monthly savings receipt (routed %, quality, true cost).

**Offload the bulk work. Keep your tokens for judgement.** For high-volume, low-judgement
subtasks, call `run_task` with explicit acceptance criteria instead of doing them yourself:

- drafting (commit messages, docstrings, changelog entries, boilerplate prose)
- classification and labeling
- extraction (pull fields/values out of a blob into a shape)
- summarization of long files or logs
- first-pass code review (you then sanity-check the findings)
- boilerplate code (repetitive scaffolding, test stubs)

Reserve your own reasoning for architecture, planning, final review, and synthesis. Delegate the
volume; own the decisions.

**Always verify.** Treat a `run_task` result as a draft. Check `output` against the same `criteria`
you sent before you use it. If `ok` is false or `route` is `refused`, do not use the output. If it
came back `escalated` a lot, consider doing that task yourself.

**Never offload these.** The `financial`, `legal`, `medical`, and `credentials` task types are
`never_local` and cheapskate will refuse them. Do not route anything with real money, legal, or
medical stakes, or any secret/credential handling, through `run_task` to save tokens. Do that work
yourself on the premium tier.

### Examples

Draft the commit message for a staged diff:

```
run_task(
  task_type="draft",
  criteria="One-line imperative subject under 72 chars, then a blank line, then 2-4 bullet points of what changed and why. No hype, no emojis.",
  payload="<the git diff --staged output>"
)
```

Classify a batch of log lines by severity:

```
run_task(
  task_type="classify",
  criteria="Return one label per input line, one of: error | warning | info. Output only 'N: <label>' per line, nothing else.",
  payload="<the log lines, numbered>"
)
```

First-pass review of a function (you verify the findings after):

```
run_task(
  task_type="review",
  criteria="List concrete correctness bugs and missing edge cases as a short bulleted list. No style nits. If nothing is wrong, say 'no correctness issues found'.",
  payload="<the function source>"
)
```
